        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3579899182" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7277124099455543937">The second of Bruce Catton’s three part masterpiece about The Army of the Potomac, covers the middle part of the war, after Antietam to the aftermath of Gettysburg. Full of marvelous prose, the story follows the army, both the generals and the privates, and everyone in between. But it also manages to move from the White House to Main Street in a fluid and insightful way. However, since the focus is on The Army of the Potomac, we always follow the war from the perspective of the men who tried to </span>
  <span id="freeText7277124099455543937" style="display:none">The second of Bruce Catton’s three part masterpiece about The Army of the Potomac, covers the middle part of the war, after Antietam to the aftermath of Gettysburg. Full of marvelous prose, the story follows the army, both the generals and the privates, and everyone in between. But it also manages to move from the White House to Main Street in a fluid and insightful way. However, since the focus is on The Army of the Potomac, we always follow the war from the perspective of the men who tried to guide it, never allowed the guidance of hind sight or a knowledge of Lee’s aims or dispositions, other than a few high level notes. During the actual battles, Catton puts you as close to the action as he can on the Union side, with Confederates pushing through the fire and smoke screaming their rebel yell. But what really makes the book so incredibly readable is the magical prose. Catton can turn a phrase in a way that most historians can only dream of, and it’s his prose that immortalizes the army and the men and women who served in it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7277124099455543937" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


