<span id="freeTextContainer2509120092488462766"><strong>Brilliant writing that sweeps the reader into Civil War</strong><br/><br/>I read this trilogy out of sequence 1 and 3 first, because I was touring Richmond and Petersburg 2 years ago and bypassed volume 2. I reread these last 2 chapters several times, due to the fact that I have visit Gettysburg half dozen times. Catton brings to life this battle like no other author I have read, this volume is a brilliant piece of writing. You will be swept up into battle Buford, Hancock, Chamberlain, Meade, Longstreet, Lee, Heat</span>
  <span id="freeText2509120092488462766" style="display:none"><strong>Brilliant writing that sweeps the reader into Civil War</strong><br /><br />I read this trilogy out of sequence 1 and 3 first, because I was touring Richmond and Petersburg 2 years ago and bypassed volume 2. I reread these last 2 chapters several times, due to the fact that I have visit Gettysburg half dozen times. Catton brings to life this battle like no other author I have read, this volume is a brilliant piece of writing. You will be swept up into battle Buford, Hancock, Chamberlain, Meade, Longstreet, Lee, Heath and Pickett. You feel the feel the Bayonet charge of the 20th Maine, the desperate moment at the Angle when the fate of the Union was in the hands of ordinary Union Soldiers holding their ground against a charge of 15,000 Confederates. Of the 3 volumes this was my favorite read!</span>
