<div id="review_3882558399" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3882558399" />
    <a title="Mac" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1079510-mac"><img alt="Mac" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3882558399?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mac" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mac" href="/user/show/1079510-mac">Mac</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1079510-mac?shelf=civil-war">civil-war</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3882558399" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13923052776907310874">&quot;Glory Road&quot; is the second book in Bruce Catton&apos;s trilogy about the Army of the Potomac. This volume covers the period from the lead-up to the Battle of Fredericksburg through the Battle of Gettysburg and its immediate aftermath. <br/><br/>For me, the best parts of the book were its last two chapters, which covered developments in the Northern homefront during the war (Molly Maguires, Copperheads, draft riots, etc.) and the Battle of Gettysburg, respectively. In contrast, I was disappointed with Catton&apos;s </span>
  <span id="freeText13923052776907310874" style="display:none">"Glory Road" is the second book in Bruce Catton's trilogy about the Army of the Potomac. This volume covers the period from the lead-up to the Battle of Fredericksburg through the Battle of Gettysburg and its immediate aftermath. <br /><br />For me, the best parts of the book were its last two chapters, which covered developments in the Northern homefront during the war (Molly Maguires, Copperheads, draft riots, etc.) and the Battle of Gettysburg, respectively. In contrast, I was disappointed with Catton's discussion of the Battle of Chancellorsville. He seems to buy into the myths about the battle and about General Joseph Hooker that were propagated by Darius Couch, Hooker's underling and rival. I highly recommend readers check out Stephen Sears's book on the battle for a more nuanced and scholarly treatment of the issues.<br /><br />It is quite interesting to read a book about the Civil War that is purely from the Northern perspective. Catton does not try to get inside the head of Robert E. Lee or Stonewall Jackson in the way of most historians of the war. I look forward to seeing how Catton completed the trilogy and the war in Stillness at Appomattox.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13923052776907310874" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

